WEBVTT

1
00:00:10.844 --> 00:00:12.804
- 2701!
Get the fuck out!

2
00:00:12.846 --> 00:00:14.305
- Is there
a MedicAlert bracelet?

3
00:00:14.389 --> 00:00:16.808
{\an8}- Did you get an ID on him?
- Student ID.

4
00:00:16.891 --> 00:00:18.768
{\an8}Name says Jackson Davis.
- That's a start.

5
00:00:18.810 --> 00:00:21.187
{\an8}Jackson. what's going on?
- Title 18!

6
00:00:21.271 --> 00:00:22.814
Title section 508!
- Javadi. you're with us.

7
00:00:22.856 --> 00:00:24.607
- We're gonna take good care
of you. Mr. Davis.

8
00:00:24.649 --> 00:00:26.067
You're in a safe place.
- You're okay.

9
00:00:26.151 --> 00:00:27.235
- Get off!
- Trauma One.

10
00:00:27.318 --> 00:00:28.820
- Reasonableness! 2709!
- Okay. okay. Jackson.

11
00:00:28.903 --> 00:00:29.821
We're gonna need you
to calm down

12
00:00:29.904 --> 00:00:31.573
to get the Taser barbs
out of your neck.

13
00:00:31.656 --> 00:00:33.324
- Do you need to jump on that?
- Mm-mm.

14
00:00:33.366 --> 00:00:35.660
Covering calls for Dana.

15
00:00:35.702 --> 00:00:37.412
- Stop talking to me.

16
00:00:37.495 --> 00:00:39.372
You can't! Title 2710--

17
00:00:39.456 --> 00:00:41.041
- Hard to assess pupils.
- [grunts]

18
00:00:41.124 --> 00:00:42.792
Hard to assess anything.
- Yeah. yeah.

19
00:00:42.834 --> 00:00:44.002
Wait till after he's sedated.

20
00:00:44.085 --> 00:00:45.545
- 10 of olanzapine.
- No. no.

21
00:00:45.628 --> 00:00:47.005
That'll take 15 minutes
to kick in.

22
00:00:47.088 --> 00:00:49.299
Uh. 5 of droperidol
puts him down in 5.

23
00:00:49.340 --> 00:00:51.134
- No. you can't give it
without knowing his QT.

24
00:00:51.176 --> 00:00:53.845
- Two beats of a rhythm strip
before he took off the leads.

25
00:00:53.928 --> 00:00:55.305
- No.

26
00:00:55.346 --> 00:00:56.848
You can't be in here.
Get out!

27
00:00:56.890 --> 00:00:58.516
- That looks good.
Go with the droperidol.

28
00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:00.685
- Get the fuck out!
Get off me!

29
00:01:00.727 --> 00:01:02.520
- Do we take
the Taser barbs out?

30
00:01:02.562 --> 00:01:04.022
- 2701.
- No.

31
00:01:04.064 --> 00:01:05.607
We got to wait
till he calms down first.

32
00:01:05.690 --> 00:01:08.318
- Get off me. man.
2901. get out!

33
00:01:08.359 --> 00:01:10.195
Get out!
2710.

34
00:01:10.278 --> 00:01:12.739
Title 18. section--
1938.

35
00:01:12.822 --> 00:01:16.201
- Mr. Randall.
happy 20th anniversary

36
00:01:16.284 --> 00:01:18.369
and a very happy
Fourth of July.

37
00:01:18.411 --> 00:01:20.205
But no sex fireworks
for you tonight.

38
00:01:20.246 --> 00:01:21.498
Give everything
a chance to heal.

39
00:01:21.539 --> 00:01:23.166
- Don't worry. I will.

40
00:01:23.208 --> 00:01:25.168
Thanks. Doc.
Ow.

41
00:01:25.210 --> 00:01:27.128
- We're going right back
through here. okay. ma'am?

42
00:01:27.212 --> 00:01:28.379
- Oh. thank you.

43
00:01:28.463 --> 00:01:30.006
- Change the dressing
twice a day.

44
00:01:30.048 --> 00:01:32.967
Doggy bag of the ointment
and nonstick gauze.

45
00:01:33.051 --> 00:01:34.469
- Cool.
I know the drill.

46
00:01:34.552 --> 00:01:36.221
Come back if it starts
to ache or stink.

47
00:01:36.262 --> 00:01:38.306
- Exactly.
Good luck. Stay safe.

48
00:01:38.389 --> 00:01:39.974
- Oh. shit. it's Daddy.
with your daddy.

49
00:01:40.058 --> 00:01:42.685
- Lord. what'd
they get up to now?

50
00:01:42.727 --> 00:01:44.229
- Treatin' and streetin'.

51
00:01:44.312 --> 00:01:46.523
- "Pros from Dover."

52
00:01:46.564 --> 00:01:47.941
- I'm sorry. Ms. Graham.

53
00:01:48.024 --> 00:01:50.235
I just saw the ASL note
in your chart.

54
00:01:50.318 --> 00:01:51.861
This is Lindsey.

55
00:01:51.903 --> 00:01:55.281
We'll bring you back
as soon as possible.

56
00:01:55.365 --> 00:01:56.574
Stay with her.

57
00:01:56.616 --> 00:01:57.909
[indistinct chatter]

58
00:01:57.992 --> 00:02:00.578
All right.
Who here needs help?

59
00:02:00.662 --> 00:02:02.664
[indistinct chatter]

60
00:02:02.747 --> 00:02:04.165
You?
You need help?

61
00:02:04.249 --> 00:02:06.918
- Oh. no. no. no. ma'am.
I've been on these since 1987.

62
00:02:07.001 --> 00:02:09.337
This one here.
he got dizzy. fell down.

63
00:02:09.420 --> 00:02:11.589
- Forgot
my blood-pressure medication.

64
00:02:11.631 --> 00:02:14.425
I left it back home in Georgia.

65
00:02:15.969 --> 00:02:17.428
- And presto.

66
00:02:17.512 --> 00:02:20.223
We're back. Mr. Digby.
with some IV antibiotics.

67
00:02:20.265 --> 00:02:23.893
First we scrub your outsides.
then we clean your insides.

68
00:02:23.935 --> 00:02:25.770
What do you need to document
in his chart?

69
00:02:25.854 --> 00:02:27.939
- Uh. time started.
time completed.

70
00:02:28.022 --> 00:02:29.440
and any adverse reactions.

71
00:02:29.482 --> 00:02:32.068
- What else?

72
00:02:32.110 --> 00:02:35.613
- Um. lot number
on the antibiotic vial.

73
00:02:35.655 --> 00:02:37.365
- Excellent.
Mr. Digby.

74
00:02:37.448 --> 00:02:38.950
- It's just Digby.

75
00:02:39.033 --> 00:02:41.744
- Digby. why'd you wait
so long to come see us?

76
00:02:43.288 --> 00:02:45.623
- I don't like
going to doctors.

77
00:02:45.665 --> 00:02:46.958
- Well. that makes two of us.

78
00:02:47.041 --> 00:02:48.668
We all need help
from time to time.

79
00:02:48.751 --> 00:02:51.504
Think maybe we could arrange
for some ongoing care?

80
00:02:51.588 --> 00:02:54.465
- I just kind of want
to get patched up. you know?

81
00:02:54.507 --> 00:02:56.134
- I do know.

82
00:02:56.217 --> 00:02:59.554
But that's today.
What's tomorrow?

83
00:02:59.637 --> 00:03:01.639
- Sunday.

84
00:03:01.681 --> 00:03:04.559
- Use the system.
That's what it's there for.

85
00:03:04.642 --> 00:03:07.103
Buddy of mine. Dylan.
knows all the angles.

86
00:03:07.145 --> 00:03:09.439
He even works
the occasional miracle.

87
00:03:09.480 --> 00:03:11.983
You think maybe
I could have him stop by?

88
00:03:13.985 --> 00:03:15.486
- I guess. yeah.

89
00:03:15.528 --> 00:03:16.529
- Great.

90
00:03:16.613 --> 00:03:18.656
How about a sandwich?
- Yeah.

91
00:03:18.698 --> 00:03:20.575
Yes. please.

92
00:03:23.119 --> 00:03:24.495
<i>- We always offer.</i>

93
00:03:24.579 --> 00:03:27.290
Two most important things--
that they know we're here

94
00:03:27.332 --> 00:03:29.667
and that we'll never
stop offering.

95
00:03:29.751 --> 00:03:31.085
- Thanks for covering.
Princess.

96
00:03:31.169 --> 00:03:32.503
- Anytime.

97
00:03:32.587 --> 00:03:34.339
- Yo. can I get
some help over here?

98
00:03:34.422 --> 00:03:36.090
- Yeah.
What's going on. man?

99
00:03:36.174 --> 00:03:37.842
- The crazy kid in there.
screaming.

100
00:03:37.926 --> 00:03:39.844
- All right. have a seat.
- Yeah. that's him.

101
00:03:39.886 --> 00:03:41.471
Still going nuts.

102
00:03:41.512 --> 00:03:43.806
Probably meth--
fucking animal.

103
00:03:43.848 --> 00:03:45.808
- What's your name. sir?
- You don't understand!

104
00:03:45.850 --> 00:03:48.019
- Tony Chinchiolo.
campus security.

105
00:03:48.061 --> 00:03:49.687
Yeah. I was at work
when this happened.

106
00:03:49.729 --> 00:03:51.856
so I'm gonna need
everything documented.

107
00:03:51.898 --> 00:03:53.191
- Okay.

108
00:03:53.233 --> 00:03:55.860
- All right.
Heart rate's 89.

109
00:03:55.902 --> 00:03:57.570
Pulse ox 97.

110
00:03:57.654 --> 00:03:59.072
Scalp lac's tiny--

111
00:03:59.155 --> 00:04:00.073
5 millimeters.
- Ow.

112
00:04:00.156 --> 00:04:01.866
- Should hold together
with Dermabond.

113
00:04:01.908 --> 00:04:03.868
- Kid threw
a fucking chair at me.

114
00:04:03.910 --> 00:04:05.787
- Work-related injury
gets a full exam.

115
00:04:05.870 --> 00:04:07.872
Jesse here will take you.
- Oh. no.

116
00:04:07.956 --> 00:04:09.374
I-I'm gonna stay here
till the cops come

117
00:04:09.457 --> 00:04:12.210
so I can give my statement
and so I can watch him.

118
00:04:12.252 --> 00:04:13.711
- Yeah.

119
00:04:13.753 --> 00:04:16.839
- Trust me. you do not want
him getting out of there.

120
00:04:16.881 --> 00:04:19.425
Ow. fuck.

121
00:04:19.509 --> 00:04:23.054
- Did she say anything?
- No more than she said to you.

122
00:04:23.137 --> 00:04:25.431
Nothing going on at home.
Nothing at school.

123
00:04:25.515 --> 00:04:28.101
- And you believe her?
- There's some flags.

124
00:04:28.184 --> 00:04:30.353
Bruising in various stages
of healing.

125
00:04:30.395 --> 00:04:31.688
She's a little withdrawn.

126
00:04:31.729 --> 00:04:33.690
doesn't engage much
for girls her age.

127
00:04:33.731 --> 00:04:36.025
But she could just be
a little shy...

128
00:04:36.067 --> 00:04:37.652
or scared of being in here.

129
00:04:37.735 --> 00:04:39.737
- Or she's being abused.

130
00:04:39.779 --> 00:04:40.905
- That too.

131
00:04:40.989 --> 00:04:42.573
We'll find out more
when Dad shows up.

132
00:04:42.657 --> 00:04:44.701
- Yep.
If he shows up.

133
00:04:47.912 --> 00:04:49.956
- I need a hand here!

134
00:04:50.039 --> 00:04:53.418
[object snaps]
- There's the first barb out.

135
00:04:53.501 --> 00:04:55.211
All right. Javadi. you're up.

136
00:04:55.253 --> 00:04:57.880
[monitor beeping]

137
00:04:57.922 --> 00:04:59.716
Okay. so you're gonna
want to clamp

138
00:04:59.757 --> 00:05:02.260
where the shaft meets the barb.

139
00:05:02.302 --> 00:05:03.469
- Mm-hmm.
- Yep.

140
00:05:03.553 --> 00:05:05.430
Stabilize the skin.

141
00:05:05.513 --> 00:05:07.932
- Not so close
so as to stick yourself.

142
00:05:07.974 --> 00:05:09.350
I've seen that once or twice.

143
00:05:09.434 --> 00:05:11.769
- Uh. pull up at 90 degrees.

144
00:05:11.853 --> 00:05:13.563
- Harder.
Yep.

145
00:05:13.604 --> 00:05:14.897
Harder.

146
00:05:14.939 --> 00:05:15.898
- Oh.

147
00:05:15.940 --> 00:05:17.900
Do we suture those?

148
00:05:17.942 --> 00:05:19.569
- Nope. just a Band-Aid.

149
00:05:19.610 --> 00:05:22.071
- Mel. we need orders.
- Right.

150
00:05:22.113 --> 00:05:23.114
- I got a rainbow.

151
00:05:23.197 --> 00:05:25.783
- Uh. CBC...

152
00:05:25.825 --> 00:05:29.078
CMP. UA. blood alcohol.
and tox screen.

153
00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:30.455
- All of the above.

154
00:05:30.538 --> 00:05:31.789
- Cap. if this
young man's stable.

155
00:05:31.873 --> 00:05:33.249
can he go to Central 10 pronto?

156
00:05:33.291 --> 00:05:34.459
Double trauma at the back door.

157
00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:36.544
- Okay. you heard the boss.
Let's get going.

158
00:05:36.627 --> 00:05:39.088
Today is starting to heat up.

159
00:05:39.130 --> 00:05:42.717
[indistinct chatter.
telephone ringing]

160
00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:45.636
- Mark Yee. 32-year-old
restrained driver.

161
00:05:45.678 --> 00:05:47.055
auto versus motorcycle.

162
00:05:47.138 --> 00:05:49.599
Altered with normal BP.
satting 99 on 2 liters.

163
00:05:49.640 --> 00:05:51.601
- We're at
the hospital now. Mark.

164
00:05:51.642 --> 00:05:53.353
What's wrong with him?
Why isn't he talking?

165
00:05:53.436 --> 00:05:55.188
- His wife. Nancy.
front-seat passenger.

166
00:05:55.271 --> 00:05:56.814
declined transport.
- I'm fine.

167
00:05:56.856 --> 00:06:00.026
We weren't going all that fast.
The motorcycle ran the light.

168
00:06:00.109 --> 00:06:02.153
- I'm Dr. Robby.
This is Dr. Al-Hashimi.

169
00:06:02.236 --> 00:06:03.654
- Nice to meet you.
- And this is Nurse Dana.

170
00:06:03.696 --> 00:06:04.864
She's our charge nurse.

171
00:06:04.947 --> 00:06:06.407
We need to look over
your husband.

172
00:06:06.491 --> 00:06:07.825
- Hello. Let's step over here
for a minute. hon.

173
00:06:07.867 --> 00:06:09.118
Let them get to work. okay?

174
00:06:09.160 --> 00:06:11.162
Antoine. Larry.
transfer out here.

175
00:06:11.245 --> 00:06:12.622
T-1 will be open in a sec.

176
00:06:12.663 --> 00:06:13.998
- Aye. aye. Cap.

177
00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:16.334
- One. two. three.

178
00:06:16.376 --> 00:06:18.086
[grunts]
- Incoming.

179
00:06:18.169 --> 00:06:19.796
- Okay. Joy. you stay with me.

180
00:06:19.837 --> 00:06:22.215
Samira. you stay
with Dr. Al-Hashimi.

181
00:06:24.050 --> 00:06:25.343
- Open skull fracture.

182
00:06:25.385 --> 00:06:26.969
Tubed him
for agonal respirations.

183
00:06:27.011 --> 00:06:28.679
BP 60 palp initially.

184
00:06:28.763 --> 00:06:31.140
Started a liter of NS.
but lost his pulse en route.

185
00:06:32.975 --> 00:06:35.019
- Oh. boy.
this doesn't look good.

186
00:06:35.061 --> 00:06:36.562
- One. two. three.

187
00:06:36.646 --> 00:06:38.439
[grunts]
Joy. check his pupils.

188
00:06:38.523 --> 00:06:39.899
Somebody hand me
a pair of scissors.

189
00:06:44.529 --> 00:06:46.030
- 8 millimeters.
Nonreactive.

190
00:06:46.114 --> 00:06:48.950
- AKA blown pupils.
fixed and dilated.

191
00:06:49.033 --> 00:06:50.326
Oh.
[groans]

192
00:06:50.368 --> 00:06:52.120
- Crushed skull with tons
of gray matter extravasation.

193
00:06:52.203 --> 00:06:53.663
At least it was quick.

194
00:06:53.704 --> 00:06:55.540
- No helmet?
- Nope. 'cause he took

195
00:06:55.581 --> 00:06:56.999
the PennDOT
Motorcycle Safety Course.

196
00:06:57.041 --> 00:06:58.376
- Isn't that
what you took. Robby?

197
00:06:58.459 --> 00:07:01.254
- Hold compressions.
Yes. but I still wear a helmet.

198
00:07:01.337 --> 00:07:03.381
Is he a donor?
- Also nope.

199
00:07:03.464 --> 00:07:04.715
- That is too bad.

200
00:07:04.757 --> 00:07:07.427
Asystole.
I think we are done here.

201
00:07:07.510 --> 00:07:09.220
- What's next door?
- The guy who hit him.

202
00:07:09.303 --> 00:07:10.680
Joy. you're with me.

203
00:07:10.721 --> 00:07:13.391
- What about a moment
of reflection? I thought--

204
00:07:13.433 --> 00:07:15.143
- He'll still be dead
when we get back.

205
00:07:15.226 --> 00:07:18.187
- Pulse ox 99.
BP 108 over 72.

206
00:07:18.229 --> 00:07:19.230
- EFAST negative.

207
00:07:19.313 --> 00:07:20.565
- Hell of a lot better
than the guy next door.

208
00:07:20.606 --> 00:07:21.899
- How's the airway?
- Good volume.

209
00:07:21.983 --> 00:07:24.235
Good sats.
Gag reflex...

210
00:07:24.318 --> 00:07:26.195
- [gags]
- Present.

211
00:07:26.237 --> 00:07:27.738
- Intubate?
- Maybe.

212
00:07:27.780 --> 00:07:28.906
Maybe not.
- Mr. Yee?

213
00:07:28.990 --> 00:07:30.741
Joy. sternal rub
on his chest. like this.

214
00:07:30.783 --> 00:07:31.909
Really hard. please.

215
00:07:31.993 --> 00:07:33.911
Mr. Yee?
- [groans]

216
00:07:33.995 --> 00:07:36.080
- Spontaneous eye movement.
Responds to pain.

217
00:07:36.164 --> 00:07:38.082
GCS is 10.
Borderline for intubation.

218
00:07:38.166 --> 00:07:41.002
- No muscle tone--flaccid
paralysis in the left arm.

219
00:07:41.085 --> 00:07:42.587
- Same on the right.
- And both legs.

220
00:07:42.628 --> 00:07:44.589
- Add towels to both sides of
the collar for more stability.

221
00:07:44.630 --> 00:07:46.757
Let's not make this worse.

222
00:07:46.841 --> 00:07:49.719
- Pan scan with 3D
reconstruction of the spine.

223
00:07:49.760 --> 00:07:51.179
- He's quadriplegic?

224
00:07:51.262 --> 00:07:53.598
- If so. it's
a low cervical injury.

225
00:07:53.639 --> 00:07:55.766
- Why is that. Joy?
- Uh...

226
00:07:55.808 --> 00:07:59.645
- C3. 4. and 5 helps you
breathe to stay alive.

227
00:07:59.729 --> 00:08:01.272
<i>- Mr. Montrose...</i>

228
00:08:01.314 --> 00:08:04.108
you can't just be wandering
around. talking to patients.

229
00:08:04.150 --> 00:08:05.943
- Well. that's--
that's what I do.

230
00:08:05.985 --> 00:08:07.487
I'm a greeter at Walmart.

231
00:08:07.570 --> 00:08:11.032
I get paid to wander
and to talk to folks.

232
00:08:11.115 --> 00:08:13.284
- Well. as a--
as a personal favor to me.

233
00:08:13.367 --> 00:08:16.454
can you at least stay
in your general vicinity?

234
00:08:16.496 --> 00:08:18.623
I can get you a wheelchair
while we wait for your X-rays.

235
00:08:18.706 --> 00:08:19.957
but it might take a minute.

236
00:08:20.041 --> 00:08:21.459
- [clears throat]
My dear. I cannot sit.

237
00:08:21.542 --> 00:08:23.544
My backside is killing me
from where I fell on it.

238
00:08:23.628 --> 00:08:26.130
which is an embarrassing
admission to make

239
00:08:26.172 --> 00:08:28.799
to such a lovely woman.
- [chuckles]

240
00:08:28.883 --> 00:08:30.426
Well. thank you
for the compliment.

241
00:08:30.468 --> 00:08:32.178
but there's no need
to be embarrassed.

242
00:08:32.261 --> 00:08:33.679
You took a very nasty fall.

243
00:08:33.763 --> 00:08:36.599
- Well. then may I say that
one look in your beautiful eyes

244
00:08:36.641 --> 00:08:38.809
and I think I'm falling again.

245
00:08:38.851 --> 00:08:42.104
[both laughing]

246
00:08:42.146 --> 00:08:43.523
- What a charmer.

247
00:08:43.606 --> 00:08:45.816
Just for that. I'm gonna
get you a foam donut.

248
00:08:45.858 --> 00:08:48.152
It's the eighth wonder
of the world.

249
00:08:48.236 --> 00:08:50.655
- Pretty great laugh
you got there. Doc.

250
00:08:50.738 --> 00:08:52.657
- [chuckles]

251
00:08:52.698 --> 00:08:54.992
Oh. God.
My witch's cackle?

252
00:08:55.076 --> 00:08:56.827
- Got CT results
for Mr. Williams.

253
00:08:56.869 --> 00:08:58.412
- Ah.

254
00:09:00.748 --> 00:09:02.833
Oh. wow.

255
00:09:04.752 --> 00:09:06.003
Okay.

256
00:09:06.087 --> 00:09:07.505
- Okay.

257
00:09:07.588 --> 00:09:09.757
- Ah.
Right on time.

258
00:09:09.840 --> 00:09:11.842
Just--just getting full.

259
00:09:11.884 --> 00:09:13.678
Yeah. I'm ready
for number five.

260
00:09:13.719 --> 00:09:15.513
- That's impressive.
- Uh-huh.

261
00:09:15.596 --> 00:09:17.765
- Yeah. there's more
where that came from.

262
00:09:17.848 --> 00:09:21.519
Although. uh. my intake
is running low.

263
00:09:21.602 --> 00:09:23.354
- Yeah. well. two more bottles
ought to do it.

264
00:09:23.396 --> 00:09:25.314
Then we'll drain your tooth.
and we'll get you out of here

265
00:09:25.356 --> 00:09:27.775
before the fireworks tonight.
- Oh.

266
00:09:27.858 --> 00:09:28.985
- Okay. Clamped.

267
00:09:29.026 --> 00:09:31.862
Ogilvie. make the change.

268
00:09:31.946 --> 00:09:34.740
- Okay.
- Mm-hmm.

269
00:09:34.824 --> 00:09:37.827
- All right.
Let her rip.

270
00:09:37.868 --> 00:09:40.329
- Flowing like a river.
- [chuckles]

271
00:09:40.371 --> 00:09:43.207
I love me some fireworks.

272
00:09:43.249 --> 00:09:45.209
- Oh. yeah?

273
00:09:45.293 --> 00:09:48.212
- Shit. I-I met Mr. Zambelli...

274
00:09:48.296 --> 00:09:50.006
- Lean forward.

275
00:09:50.047 --> 00:09:52.091
- Many times on the field.

276
00:09:52.174 --> 00:09:54.760
- Who's Mr. Zambelli?

277
00:09:54.844 --> 00:09:56.262
- Son. you don't know fireworks

278
00:09:56.345 --> 00:09:58.848
if you don't know
the name Zambelli.

279
00:09:58.889 --> 00:10:00.808
He helped Pittsburgh become

280
00:10:00.891 --> 00:10:03.394
the firework capital
of America.

281
00:10:03.477 --> 00:10:05.730
You did know that. didn't you?

282
00:10:05.813 --> 00:10:07.398
- No.
- Ah.

283
00:10:07.481 --> 00:10:10.735
Y'all don't know nothing
about pyrotechnics.

284
00:10:10.776 --> 00:10:12.194
Stick to doctoring.

285
00:10:12.236 --> 00:10:14.405
- Yes. will do.

286
00:10:20.411 --> 00:10:24.206
- [sighs] I'm sure you have
some questions.

287
00:10:24.248 --> 00:10:27.585
I know it's a lot to take in.

288
00:10:27.668 --> 00:10:30.046
- It's a tumor.

289
00:10:30.087 --> 00:10:31.213
It's a brain tumor.

290
00:10:31.255 --> 00:10:34.300
- Well. it's a mass.
about 4 centimeters.

291
00:10:34.383 --> 00:10:36.427
in the frontal lobe.

292
00:10:37.678 --> 00:10:39.639
- Is it cancer?

293
00:10:39.722 --> 00:10:42.141
- We can't say
for sure right now.

294
00:10:42.224 --> 00:10:43.601
It could be many things--

295
00:10:43.684 --> 00:10:46.771
uh. infection. inflammation.

296
00:10:46.854 --> 00:10:49.774
a benign cyst.

297
00:10:49.815 --> 00:10:53.069
- Is it what made me fall?

298
00:10:53.110 --> 00:10:54.987
- Yeah. possibly.

299
00:10:56.906 --> 00:10:59.617
We'd like to keep you here
and treat with dexamethasone.

300
00:10:59.700 --> 00:11:01.744
which is a steroid
to take down the swelling.

301
00:11:01.786 --> 00:11:03.245
- Hmm.
- And then we'll need

302
00:11:03.287 --> 00:11:06.207
a brain biopsy
to know exactly what it is.

303
00:11:06.290 --> 00:11:10.127
- What. you're--you're gonna
cut open my head?

304
00:11:10.169 --> 00:11:12.463
- It's just a small hole.

305
00:11:12.505 --> 00:11:16.300
We'll do a-a CT-guided
stereotactical biopsy

306
00:11:16.384 --> 00:11:18.636
with a-a blunt. thin needle...
- [sighs]

307
00:11:18.719 --> 00:11:21.472
- Which sounds crazy. but it's
actually pretty amazing.

308
00:11:21.555 --> 00:11:24.475
I mean. most patients
go home the next day.

309
00:11:28.312 --> 00:11:30.648
- I don't know.

310
00:11:30.690 --> 00:11:34.151
What do you think I should do?

311
00:11:34.235 --> 00:11:37.655
- I think this is
a pretty good plan.

312
00:11:37.697 --> 00:11:39.031
- Okay.
- Yeah?

313
00:11:39.115 --> 00:11:43.119
- BP 95 over 67.

314
00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:45.121
- Seems a little
on the low side.

315
00:11:45.162 --> 00:11:46.622
- It is.

316
00:11:46.664 --> 00:11:48.833
Have you ever had
low blood pressure in the past?

317
00:11:48.874 --> 00:11:51.836
- No. sir. My blood pressure's
always high.

318
00:11:51.877 --> 00:11:54.839
- Hold still. sir.
No talking while we do the EKG.

319
00:11:54.922 --> 00:11:57.508
- The Hansens all run high.
except for Monty.

320
00:11:57.550 --> 00:11:59.885
He ran low. but he's dead.
- That's not helpful.

321
00:11:59.969 --> 00:12:02.805
You want to help.
quit playing family pharmacist.

322
00:12:02.847 --> 00:12:05.266
- Pooling meds is how
we've always done it.

323
00:12:05.349 --> 00:12:06.600
You put everything
in a big pile

324
00:12:06.684 --> 00:12:07.852
in the middle of the table--

325
00:12:07.893 --> 00:12:09.186
- Well. look where
that got us now.

326
00:12:09.228 --> 00:12:11.313
- No. I'm gonna jump in here
and echo that sharing meds

327
00:12:11.355 --> 00:12:12.481
which haven't been
prescribed to you

328
00:12:12.523 --> 00:12:13.774
is actually a real big no-no.

329
00:12:13.858 --> 00:12:14.817
How we doing on remembering

330
00:12:14.859 --> 00:12:16.193
what your brother
might've taken?

331
00:12:16.277 --> 00:12:17.361
- We could call
back to the house.

332
00:12:17.445 --> 00:12:19.989
- Great idea.
Okay.

333
00:12:20.030 --> 00:12:22.366
Whatever little round pill
you took. sir.

334
00:12:22.408 --> 00:12:24.452
has caused your heart rate
and blood pressure

335
00:12:24.535 --> 00:12:26.704
to drop so low.
you're at risk of fainting.

336
00:12:26.746 --> 00:12:28.873
falling. or having
a serious injury.

337
00:12:28.914 --> 00:12:29.999
- Oh.

338
00:12:30.040 --> 00:12:31.625
- We need to take
him back to the ER

339
00:12:31.709 --> 00:12:32.710
so he can get
a liter of fluids.

340
00:12:32.752 --> 00:12:34.044
we can check his blood tests

341
00:12:34.086 --> 00:12:35.379
and monitor his heart rate
and blood pressure

342
00:12:35.421 --> 00:12:37.548
till he recovers.

343
00:12:37.590 --> 00:12:39.216
- Pulse ox holding steady
at 99.

344
00:12:39.258 --> 00:12:40.384
Good tidal volume.

345
00:12:40.426 --> 00:12:42.052
- How you doing there. Mr. Yee?

346
00:12:42.094 --> 00:12:43.387
- Scanner can take him now.

347
00:12:43.471 --> 00:12:44.722
- I'll check the results
from upstairs.

348
00:12:44.805 --> 00:12:47.516
- Why is he so altered?
- Could be concussion.

349
00:12:47.558 --> 00:12:49.393
Maybe a small
intracranial hemorrhage.

350
00:12:49.477 --> 00:12:51.937
- All will be revealed
by the Donut of Truth.

351
00:12:52.021 --> 00:12:54.607
- Need a portable monitor.
- Joy. stay with him. please.

352
00:12:54.690 --> 00:12:56.567
See if the radiologist
can give us a STAT read.

353
00:12:56.650 --> 00:12:57.693
- How is he?

354
00:12:57.735 --> 00:13:00.070
Did I hear someone
say he's paralyzed?

355
00:13:00.112 --> 00:13:02.406
- There are signs of weakness
in both arms and legs.

356
00:13:02.448 --> 00:13:04.742
But before we can make
any prognosis.

357
00:13:04.825 --> 00:13:06.076
we'll need a full-body scan.

358
00:13:06.160 --> 00:13:08.412
- Head CT will show us
any brain injury.

359
00:13:08.496 --> 00:13:10.581
Neck CT will show us
any spinal-cord injury.

360
00:13:10.664 --> 00:13:13.334
Chest. abdomen. pelvis will
rule out any internal bleeding.

361
00:13:13.417 --> 00:13:14.418
- Oh. my God.

362
00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:17.254
- The scans should only take
about 15 minutes.

363
00:13:17.338 --> 00:13:20.090
In the meantime. perhaps you'd
let us look you over as well?

364
00:13:20.132 --> 00:13:22.384
- I'm fine.
The medics checked me.

365
00:13:22.426 --> 00:13:24.929
I just want to stay
with my husband.

366
00:13:24.970 --> 00:13:27.181
- Well. you can't go
into the CT with him.

367
00:13:27.264 --> 00:13:29.433
but you can wait just outside
if you like.

368
00:13:29.475 --> 00:13:30.726
- Excuse me.
- Princess. this is Nancy.

369
00:13:30.768 --> 00:13:32.353
Mrs. Yee is gonna go
with her husband to CT.

370
00:13:32.436 --> 00:13:33.437
Will you show her where to go?

371
00:13:33.521 --> 00:13:36.190
- Sure. Come on in.
- Thank you.

372
00:13:37.983 --> 00:13:39.777
- So what's the plan now?

373
00:13:39.860 --> 00:13:41.946
Keep observing me
in my natural habitat?

374
00:13:42.029 --> 00:13:43.405
No telling
what I might do next.

375
00:13:43.447 --> 00:13:44.949
- I think I've got the gist.

376
00:13:45.032 --> 00:13:47.117
How about we each take a lap
and meet here

377
00:13:47.159 --> 00:13:48.619
when Mr. Yee is back from CT?

378
00:13:48.661 --> 00:13:50.496
- Splitting up so soon?

379
00:13:50.579 --> 00:13:53.666
- You're free to see
other people. Dr. Robinavitch.

380
00:13:53.749 --> 00:13:56.502
I'm looking for cooperation.
not commitment.

381
00:13:58.379 --> 00:14:01.006
- [chuckles]
[device whirs]

382
00:14:01.090 --> 00:14:03.092
- So you bandaged
the burn yourself?

383
00:14:03.133 --> 00:14:04.844
- Oh. no. no. no. no.
no. no. no. no--

384
00:14:04.927 --> 00:14:06.971
- Ma'am. you're--you're making
it difficult for me

385
00:14:07.012 --> 00:14:08.639
to see under this dressing.

386
00:14:08.722 --> 00:14:11.976
Is that a tablecloth?
- Part of a window curtain.

387
00:14:12.059 --> 00:14:13.394
Cleaner than tablecloth.

388
00:14:13.477 --> 00:14:15.104
I'll wait for the doctor.
Thank you.

389
00:14:15.145 --> 00:14:18.482
- May I ask how this happened?

390
00:14:18.566 --> 00:14:20.276
- For weeks on end.
the kids with their

391
00:14:20.317 --> 00:14:22.570
<i>guchnyy</i> firecrackers.
going all day and night.

392
00:14:22.653 --> 00:14:24.655
- Oh. i-is this
a firecracker burn?

393
00:14:24.697 --> 00:14:27.658
- No. sweetie.
this is from the full samovar

394
00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:30.578
I drop on the floor
when the sh--

395
00:14:30.661 --> 00:14:33.163
the firecrackers
started going on again.

396
00:14:33.247 --> 00:14:35.165
- I'm sorry.
What's a samovar?

397
00:14:35.207 --> 00:14:38.419
- It is a big metal urn
for coffee or tea.

398
00:14:38.502 --> 00:14:40.504
They can get super-duper hot.

399
00:14:40.588 --> 00:14:42.798
and I was never allowed
to touch ours.

400
00:14:42.840 --> 00:14:44.174
Uh. hello. Mrs. Kovalenko.

401
00:14:44.258 --> 00:14:45.509
My name is
Dr. Michael Robinavitch.

402
00:14:45.551 --> 00:14:47.177
Everybody calls me Dr. Robby.

403
00:14:47.219 --> 00:14:50.180
- Robinavitch? Jewish?
- You guessed it.

404
00:14:50.222 --> 00:14:53.684
And I see that you are
here today for a burn.

405
00:14:53.726 --> 00:14:55.060
Why don't we take a look?

406
00:14:55.144 --> 00:14:56.687
- Oh. not married?

407
00:14:56.729 --> 00:14:58.355
- No. I'm not married.

408
00:14:58.439 --> 00:15:01.025
- [chuckles]
Do you attend synagogue?

409
00:15:01.066 --> 00:15:03.986
- Uh. not for a while.

410
00:15:04.028 --> 00:15:07.907
I mean. High Holidays mostly.

411
00:15:07.990 --> 00:15:09.074
- Where?

412
00:15:09.158 --> 00:15:10.743
- Ooh.
- [whimpers]

413
00:15:10.826 --> 00:15:13.037
- What did you put on this?

414
00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:14.663
- Where?
- On your burn.

415
00:15:14.705 --> 00:15:16.874
Is this honey?
- Yes. honey.

416
00:15:16.957 --> 00:15:18.876
Where do you go on holy days?

417
00:15:18.959 --> 00:15:21.879
- Uh. my grandparents. um--

418
00:15:21.962 --> 00:15:23.631
I grew up
going to Rodef Shalom.

419
00:15:23.714 --> 00:15:24.632
You?

420
00:15:24.715 --> 00:15:27.009
- Tree of Life.

421
00:15:28.719 --> 00:15:30.137
- They're rebuilding.

422
00:15:30.220 --> 00:15:32.556
- Yes. something new.

423
00:15:32.598 --> 00:15:36.060
Remember. Rebuild. Renew.

424
00:15:36.101 --> 00:15:38.520
That's the slogan.

425
00:15:40.564 --> 00:15:43.233
- I'm sorry.
did you say "honey"?

426
00:15:43.317 --> 00:15:45.402
- You think honey's funny?

427
00:15:45.486 --> 00:15:47.404
Works like a charm.

428
00:15:47.488 --> 00:15:49.573
My father kept bees.
I know.

429
00:15:49.615 --> 00:15:52.868
- If the honey is medical grade
and the burns are not too bad.

430
00:15:52.910 --> 00:15:54.954
honey actually does have
some antibacterial

431
00:15:55.037 --> 00:15:56.580
and anti-inflammatory
properties.

432
00:15:56.622 --> 00:15:59.124
However. these burns
are very deep in some places.

433
00:15:59.208 --> 00:16:01.543
They're going
to need debridement.

434
00:16:01.585 --> 00:16:04.546
I'm glad you came in.

435
00:16:04.588 --> 00:16:06.382
- That's what I thought.

436
00:16:06.423 --> 00:16:10.386
I was hoping no.
but I figured as much.

437
00:16:10.427 --> 00:16:11.470
- Not to worry.

438
00:16:11.553 --> 00:16:14.348
We are gonna have you
patched up and home

439
00:16:14.431 --> 00:16:16.016
in time for dinner
and fireworks.

440
00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:17.935
- No.

441
00:16:17.977 --> 00:16:19.436
No more fireworks.

442
00:16:19.478 --> 00:16:20.688
No.

443
00:16:20.771 --> 00:16:21.772
- Okay.

444
00:16:21.855 --> 00:16:26.110
- Anyone here treating
Kylie Connors?

445
00:16:26.151 --> 00:16:27.611
- She's my daughter.

446
00:16:27.653 --> 00:16:29.697
She's nine.
I'm Benny Connors.

447
00:16:29.780 --> 00:16:32.116
- Mr. Connors. I'm Dr. Santos.

448
00:16:32.199 --> 00:16:33.534
I'm treating Kylie.

449
00:16:33.617 --> 00:16:35.119
- Is she okay?
Can I see her?

450
00:16:35.160 --> 00:16:37.079
My--my girlfriend. Gina.
says she got a cut on her chin?

451
00:16:37.121 --> 00:16:38.122
- Yeah. I can take you to her.

452
00:16:38.205 --> 00:16:39.915
She has a small
laceration on her chin.

453
00:16:39.957 --> 00:16:42.126
but it was easily repaired
with medical superglue.

454
00:16:42.209 --> 00:16:44.294
so no stitches necessary.
- Okay.

455
00:16:44.378 --> 00:16:46.839
- She chipped a tooth.
but it's a baby tooth.

456
00:16:46.922 --> 00:16:48.632
so it won't need dental work.

457
00:16:48.716 --> 00:16:50.592
- All right.
well. that's a relief.

458
00:16:50.634 --> 00:16:53.095
- Has Kylie had
any previous injuries?

459
00:16:53.137 --> 00:16:54.763
- Uh. yeah.

460
00:16:54.805 --> 00:16:56.974
She. um--she broke
her wrist last year.

461
00:16:57.057 --> 00:16:58.642
She was skateboarding.

462
00:16:58.684 --> 00:17:01.812
- Dana. if you could get Dylan
to come to North 1.

463
00:17:01.895 --> 00:17:03.939
and Ahmad.
- You bet.

464
00:17:03.981 --> 00:17:06.275
- Okay. I got it now.
One. two. three.

465
00:17:06.316 --> 00:17:07.484
- Daddy. you came.

466
00:17:07.568 --> 00:17:09.319
- Baby. what's going on. huh?

467
00:17:09.403 --> 00:17:11.030
- My tooth broke.
and my chin got cut.

468
00:17:11.113 --> 00:17:14.324
- Oh. no.
[smooches]

469
00:17:14.366 --> 00:17:15.492
What happened?

470
00:17:15.576 --> 00:17:17.786
- She was running
up the stairs.

471
00:17:17.828 --> 00:17:20.456
- Gina was chasing me.
- We were playing.

472
00:17:20.497 --> 00:17:23.000
- As I was saying. Mr. Connors.
the laceration is pretty minor.

473
00:17:23.042 --> 00:17:24.001
- On the stairs?

474
00:17:24.084 --> 00:17:26.170
- It was an accident.
- Perhaps we can--

475
00:17:26.253 --> 00:17:27.796
- An accident
that wouldn't have happened

476
00:17:27.838 --> 00:17:29.131
if you weren't running
up the stairs.

477
00:17:29.173 --> 00:17:30.299
Do you understand
what I'm saying?

478
00:17:30.340 --> 00:17:32.760
This is the last thing
that I need right now.

479
00:17:32.843 --> 00:17:34.470
is her mother finding out
that she got hurt

480
00:17:34.511 --> 00:17:36.096
when she's with you.
- It was an accident.

481
00:17:36.180 --> 00:17:37.639
And before you get
all high and mighty.

482
00:17:37.681 --> 00:17:39.600
I've got questions of my own.
- Like what?

483
00:17:39.683 --> 00:17:40.934
- Hey. Mr. Connors.

484
00:17:41.018 --> 00:17:42.811
I'm sorry. I meant to be here
when you arrived.

485
00:17:42.853 --> 00:17:44.772
I'm Dylan Easton.
I'm with Social Services.

486
00:17:44.855 --> 00:17:45.939
- We have insurance.
Thank you.

487
00:17:46.023 --> 00:17:47.566
- Perhaps we can step outside
and chat for a second?

488
00:17:47.649 --> 00:17:49.526
I can fill you in
on where we are.

489
00:17:49.568 --> 00:17:51.361
Hey. uh. Jesse. do you want
to keep Kylie entertained

490
00:17:51.445 --> 00:17:53.030
for a few minutes while I...
- Absolutely.

491
00:17:53.113 --> 00:17:54.073
- Borrow her dad?

492
00:17:54.156 --> 00:17:55.240
We'll just head down
to the family room.

493
00:17:55.324 --> 00:17:57.493
It's a little quieter there.

494
00:17:57.534 --> 00:17:59.244
- Why do I got to talk
to a social worker?

495
00:17:59.328 --> 00:18:01.747
- Anytime a child is injured.
we have some standard questions

496
00:18:01.830 --> 00:18:03.248
that we ask parents
and caregivers.

497
00:18:03.332 --> 00:18:06.418
- Good. That's fine. Great.
Ask me here.

498
00:18:06.502 --> 00:18:10.005
- Well. we noticed
some bruising on Kylie's body.

499
00:18:10.047 --> 00:18:13.383
some old. some new.
on her back and legs.

500
00:18:13.467 --> 00:18:15.594
Any idea how she got those?
- Yeah. soccer.

501
00:18:15.677 --> 00:18:16.845
She plays for a club team.

502
00:18:16.887 --> 00:18:18.097
They're. you know.
little girls.

503
00:18:18.180 --> 00:18:20.224
but they play like they're
in "The Hunger Games."

504
00:18:20.265 --> 00:18:22.309
- Well. I understand
that you and Kylie do

505
00:18:22.392 --> 00:18:25.229
a fair amount of roughhousing.

506
00:18:25.270 --> 00:18:27.231
- What?

507
00:18:27.272 --> 00:18:29.900
I'm sorry.
Are you fucking kidding me?

508
00:18:29.983 --> 00:18:31.068
Where are you going with this?

509
00:18:31.151 --> 00:18:32.402
Are you saying
that I hurt my daughter?

510
00:18:32.444 --> 00:18:33.695
- Mr. Connors.
nobody's saying that--

511
00:18:33.737 --> 00:18:34.822
- Oh. no. no. no.
no. no. no. no. no.

512
00:18:34.905 --> 00:18:36.031
Gina!
- Mr. Connors--

513
00:18:36.073 --> 00:18:37.407
- Just--just--Gina!

514
00:18:37.449 --> 00:18:38.408
- Sir. take a breath.

515
00:18:38.450 --> 00:18:39.576
- Gina. what did you say
to them?

516
00:18:39.618 --> 00:18:41.411
- Nothing.
I said that you're a great dad.

517
00:18:41.453 --> 00:18:42.913
- Okay. What else?

518
00:18:42.955 --> 00:18:44.414
- That you guys
like to wrestle.

519
00:18:44.456 --> 00:18:45.582
- Jesus Christ.
- What?

520
00:18:45.666 --> 00:18:47.084
They wanted to know where
all her bruises are from.

521
00:18:47.167 --> 00:18:49.002
- Who the fuck are you to talk
about me and my daughter?

522
00:18:49.086 --> 00:18:50.546
- Who the fuck am I?
- Yeah. that's what I'm asking.

523
00:18:50.587 --> 00:18:51.713
- Who the fuck am I?

524
00:18:51.755 --> 00:18:53.090
- Hey. big man. take
one more fucking step--

525
00:18:53.132 --> 00:18:55.467
- Hey. that's enough.
You need to calm down.

526
00:18:55.551 --> 00:18:57.469
- Hey. everybody.
back the fuck up!

527
00:18:57.553 --> 00:18:58.887
- Stop! Stop! Stop! Stop!

528
00:18:58.929 --> 00:19:01.932
Kylie's platelets
are only 9.000.

529
00:19:02.015 --> 00:19:03.934
- What does that mean?
- [sighs]

530
00:19:04.017 --> 00:19:06.812
It's--it's not what we thought.

531
00:19:06.895 --> 00:19:09.148
It's probably ITP.

532
00:19:09.231 --> 00:19:11.483
- What the hell is ITP?

533
00:19:11.567 --> 00:19:13.819
- Something we can treat.

534
00:19:19.992 --> 00:19:22.578
- You feel that?
- Mm. no.

535
00:19:22.619 --> 00:19:24.246
- Excellent.

536
00:19:24.288 --> 00:19:26.123
This is looking very good.

537
00:19:26.206 --> 00:19:28.208
- Ah. Tell Mr. Kovalenko.

538
00:19:28.292 --> 00:19:31.795
[laughter]

539
00:19:31.879 --> 00:19:33.130
- Mrs. Kovalenko?

540
00:19:33.172 --> 00:19:35.048
- Yes?
Yana. please.

541
00:19:35.132 --> 00:19:38.969
- Yana. you mentioned
that you dropped the samovar

542
00:19:39.052 --> 00:19:42.472
when you heard firecrackers.

543
00:19:42.514 --> 00:19:43.557
- Yeah.

544
00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:50.314
I was on my way inside--

545
00:19:50.355 --> 00:19:53.442
October 27. 2018--

546
00:19:53.483 --> 00:19:56.403
to the synagogue
when the shooting started.

547
00:20:01.116 --> 00:20:03.994
There was nothing I could do.

548
00:20:04.077 --> 00:20:05.662
I went in...

549
00:20:05.704 --> 00:20:08.165
after the police arrived.

550
00:20:08.248 --> 00:20:10.334
I felt I had to.

551
00:20:12.169 --> 00:20:14.338
I'm better now.

552
00:20:14.421 --> 00:20:16.840
But...

553
00:20:16.882 --> 00:20:20.177
[voice breaking]
New Year's Eve. Fourth of July.

554
00:20:20.260 --> 00:20:23.680
when--when kids have
their fireworks

555
00:20:23.764 --> 00:20:26.558
and firecrackers. I--

556
00:20:28.727 --> 00:20:31.605
- There is no clock
on how long it takes.

557
00:20:31.688 --> 00:20:33.148
- [scoffs]

558
00:20:33.190 --> 00:20:34.858
No clock.

559
00:20:34.900 --> 00:20:37.694
You must be joking.

560
00:20:37.778 --> 00:20:39.821
[knock at door]

561
00:20:39.863 --> 00:20:41.114
- Robby?
- Yep.

562
00:20:41.198 --> 00:20:43.325
- Mark Yee is back from CT.
- Oh. okay.

563
00:20:43.367 --> 00:20:44.826
Um. Perlah. why don't we go
ahead and see if we can put

564
00:20:44.868 --> 00:20:46.620
a nonstick dressing on this?

565
00:20:46.703 --> 00:20:48.872
And I will come back.
and we can discuss

566
00:20:48.956 --> 00:20:50.332
aftercare instructions.

567
00:20:50.374 --> 00:20:51.833
- Yeah. you got it. boss.

568
00:20:51.875 --> 00:20:53.961
- Thank you. Doctor.

569
00:21:00.884 --> 00:21:03.345
[door closes]

570
00:21:03.387 --> 00:21:06.098
[indistinct chatter]

571
00:21:06.181 --> 00:21:08.684
- Vitals stable.
Pulse ox holding at 99.

572
00:21:08.725 --> 00:21:10.727
- Okay.
Heart and lungs look good.

573
00:21:10.811 --> 00:21:12.896
[cell phone rings]

574
00:21:12.938 --> 00:21:15.232
- Dr. Mohan.
- Dr. Robby?

575
00:21:15.274 --> 00:21:18.527
- Yeah?
[sighs]

576
00:21:18.568 --> 00:21:21.071
- Please make him be okay.

577
00:21:21.154 --> 00:21:23.031
- I can assure you that we
are gonna do absolutely--

578
00:21:23.073 --> 00:21:25.701
- Everything you can.
I know.

579
00:21:25.742 --> 00:21:27.244
God. this is all my fault.

580
00:21:27.327 --> 00:21:30.205
- Mrs. Yee--
- Oh. he's been so stressed.

581
00:21:30.247 --> 00:21:32.582
So I planned this weekend away
at Seven Springs.

582
00:21:32.624 --> 00:21:35.168
but he didn't want to go
because of work.

583
00:21:35.252 --> 00:21:38.255
So we fought
this whole morning.

584
00:21:38.338 --> 00:21:40.757
And then I...

585
00:21:40.799 --> 00:21:44.052
I said awful things.

586
00:21:44.094 --> 00:21:46.054
Those can't be the last words
we say to each other.

587
00:21:46.096 --> 00:21:47.681
Doctor. please.

588
00:21:47.764 --> 00:21:50.600
- Good news.
CT looks normal.

589
00:21:50.684 --> 00:21:52.352
No bleeding inside the skull.

590
00:21:52.436 --> 00:21:55.188
C-spine. no fractures seen.

591
00:21:55.272 --> 00:21:57.607
- He didn't break his neck?
- Then why is he paralyzed?

592
00:21:57.649 --> 00:21:59.234
- You can have spinal injuries

593
00:21:59.276 --> 00:22:00.986
without
radiologic abnormalities.

594
00:22:01.069 --> 00:22:03.905
- Sometimes it doesn't show up
on CT. only on MRI.

595
00:22:03.947 --> 00:22:06.325
[cell phone rings]
- Dr. Mohan.

596
00:22:09.161 --> 00:22:10.287
Are you sure?

597
00:22:13.290 --> 00:22:15.083
Okay.

598
00:22:15.125 --> 00:22:17.127
Critical potassium level. 1.2.

599
00:22:17.210 --> 00:22:18.754
- Wow.

600
00:22:18.795 --> 00:22:20.339
- Okay.
- That's crazy low.

601
00:22:20.422 --> 00:22:22.424
- Uh. extremely low potassium
with generalized weakness

602
00:22:22.466 --> 00:22:24.301
and no cervical injury.

603
00:22:24.384 --> 00:22:25.635
We may be looking at--

604
00:22:25.719 --> 00:22:27.471
- Hypokalemic
periodic paralysis.

605
00:22:27.554 --> 00:22:28.638
- What is that?

606
00:22:28.680 --> 00:22:30.223
- It's a rare condition
where potassium gets shifted

607
00:22:30.307 --> 00:22:32.392
into the cells.
causing profound weakness.

608
00:22:32.476 --> 00:22:33.602
just like paralysis.

609
00:22:33.643 --> 00:22:35.312
- Will he get better?
- Yes.

610
00:22:35.354 --> 00:22:36.980
Back to normal in a few hours.

611
00:22:37.064 --> 00:22:38.315
- In a f--

612
00:22:38.398 --> 00:22:40.067
- Replete slowly.
10 MEQ of KCl--

613
00:22:40.150 --> 00:22:43.111
- [crying]
Thank you so much.

614
00:22:43.153 --> 00:22:44.654
Did you hear that. Mark?

615
00:22:44.696 --> 00:22:48.408
Oh. baby.
you're gonna get better.

616
00:22:48.492 --> 00:22:50.660
Oh. baby.

617
00:22:50.702 --> 00:22:52.496
- All right. DD.
Hey. come on now. man.

618
00:22:52.537 --> 00:22:54.414
- Oh. how you doing. Duante?

619
00:22:54.498 --> 00:22:55.999
- Fine.
- Great.

620
00:22:56.041 --> 00:22:57.417
If you're fine. you go home.

621
00:22:57.501 --> 00:22:58.502
- Really?
- Yeah.

622
00:22:58.543 --> 00:23:01.630
- Mm-mm.
Hey. tell them.

623
00:23:01.671 --> 00:23:04.174
- Me and my sister
were making bracelets.

624
00:23:04.257 --> 00:23:08.178
and I put beads up my nose.

625
00:23:08.261 --> 00:23:09.679
- How many?

626
00:23:09.763 --> 00:23:11.139
- One on each side.

627
00:23:11.181 --> 00:23:13.809
- I got to ask--
why'd you stick them up there?

628
00:23:13.850 --> 00:23:15.519
See how many will fit?

629
00:23:15.560 --> 00:23:17.396
- To shoot them out
like rockets.

630
00:23:17.479 --> 00:23:18.522
- Mm.

631
00:23:18.563 --> 00:23:19.856
- But I breathed in.

632
00:23:19.940 --> 00:23:22.859
and they went deeper
and now won't come out.

633
00:23:22.943 --> 00:23:24.694
- Did you try anything at home?

634
00:23:24.778 --> 00:23:26.363
- Yeah. I tried blowing
in his mouth.

635
00:23:26.446 --> 00:23:28.073
but just got a little snot
on my cheek.

636
00:23:28.156 --> 00:23:29.241
- "A" for effort. Dad.

637
00:23:29.324 --> 00:23:31.993
Okay. we need to take a look
with a little flashlight.

638
00:23:32.035 --> 00:23:33.870
Okay?
- Okay.

639
00:23:33.912 --> 00:23:35.372
- This is what I have
to look forward to?

640
00:23:35.455 --> 00:23:37.707
- This and so much more.

641
00:23:37.749 --> 00:23:40.335
Red bead below
the inferior turbinate.

642
00:23:40.377 --> 00:23:42.796
- I...

643
00:23:42.879 --> 00:23:44.214
got a blue one.

644
00:23:44.256 --> 00:23:46.842
Afrin. benzocaine.
Katz extractor?

645
00:23:46.883 --> 00:23:48.969
- Yep. Dad. looks like we got
to go up and get them.

646
00:23:49.052 --> 00:23:51.680
- No way he's sitting still.
- Oh. he'll be numbed up.

647
00:23:51.721 --> 00:23:52.889
- You don't know this child.

648
00:23:52.931 --> 00:23:55.892
- Hey. Duante.
you like video games?

649
00:23:55.934 --> 00:23:57.727
- Everybody does.

650
00:23:57.811 --> 00:24:00.021
- We have a 3D video game.

651
00:24:00.063 --> 00:24:01.940
- Yeah.
- Cool.

652
00:24:02.023 --> 00:24:03.150
- [chuckles]

653
00:24:06.611 --> 00:24:09.406
- That's KCl and saline
at 10 MEQ per hour.

654
00:24:09.489 --> 00:24:11.575
- We avoid dextrose
because the insulin response

655
00:24:11.616 --> 00:24:12.909
drops the K even more.

656
00:24:12.993 --> 00:24:15.745
- If it's genetic. why didn't
it happen when he was a kid?

657
00:24:15.829 --> 00:24:18.123
- It usually starts
after the teen years.

658
00:24:18.206 --> 00:24:19.249
- And it can be intermittent.

659
00:24:19.332 --> 00:24:22.377
Sometimes it's triggered
by intense exercise or stress.

660
00:24:22.419 --> 00:24:24.379
- We've been married
eight years.

661
00:24:24.421 --> 00:24:26.548
We've had fights.
He's never collapsed.

662
00:24:26.590 --> 00:24:28.049
- If his thyroid
gets overactive.

663
00:24:28.091 --> 00:24:29.885
that brings it on
later in life.

664
00:24:29.926 --> 00:24:32.429
- I ordered TSH. T3. T4.

665
00:24:32.512 --> 00:24:34.764
- So now we just wait?

666
00:24:34.848 --> 00:24:37.017
[monitors beeping rapidly]

667
00:24:37.100 --> 00:24:38.393
- Bag him.
Starting compressions.

668
00:24:38.435 --> 00:24:41.021
Charge to 200.
- What is happening?

669
00:24:41.104 --> 00:24:43.023
- Low potassium
can harm electrical activity

670
00:24:43.106 --> 00:24:44.608
in the heart.
- Charged.

671
00:24:44.649 --> 00:24:46.610
- Clear.
- Clear.

672
00:24:46.651 --> 00:24:48.487
- Resuming compressions.

673
00:24:49.988 --> 00:24:53.867
- So your little girl was ITP?
- Go figure.

674
00:24:53.950 --> 00:24:56.411
Nothing like a zebra
to kick-start your morning.

675
00:24:56.453 --> 00:24:59.039
- Well. it's better
than the alternative.

676
00:24:59.122 --> 00:25:00.624
- True.

677
00:25:00.665 --> 00:25:02.792
- ITP.

678
00:25:02.876 --> 00:25:05.295
So that's. uh. intra--

679
00:25:05.378 --> 00:25:06.963
- Immune thrombocytopenia.

680
00:25:07.047 --> 00:25:10.467
- Used to be called idiopathic
thrombocytopenic purpura.

681
00:25:10.550 --> 00:25:12.302
Know what "idiopathic" means?

682
00:25:12.385 --> 00:25:14.429
- That we don't know
the exact cause.

683
00:25:14.471 --> 00:25:16.306
- It means the patient
is pathetic

684
00:25:16.348 --> 00:25:18.808
and the doctor is an idiot.

685
00:25:20.352 --> 00:25:22.145
- Just checked
on baby Jane Doe.

686
00:25:22.229 --> 00:25:24.856
Looking good.
Taking formula well.

687
00:25:24.940 --> 00:25:26.691
- We're here
to take a statement.

688
00:25:26.775 --> 00:25:29.486
We're looking
for a Tony Chinchiolo.

689
00:25:29.569 --> 00:25:33.114
- Yo!
Right over here. boys!

690
00:25:33.156 --> 00:25:35.075
Well. officers.

691
00:25:35.158 --> 00:25:37.452
- Heard you had some trouble
over at the campus library.

692
00:25:37.494 --> 00:25:39.788
- Shit.
Let me just say--

693
00:25:39.829 --> 00:25:42.415
new appreciation
for what you guys do every day.

694
00:25:42.499 --> 00:25:44.918
Frickin' junkie jungle. right?

695
00:25:45.001 --> 00:25:47.087
- At the campus library?

696
00:25:47.170 --> 00:25:48.338
- Yeah.

697
00:25:48.380 --> 00:25:49.631
- Thumb and forefinger
make a C.

698
00:25:49.673 --> 00:25:51.341
Bottom three fingers make an E
for jaw lift.

699
00:25:51.383 --> 00:25:53.343
One breath every five seconds.
Come here. try it.

700
00:25:53.426 --> 00:25:55.262
- About two minutes
since defibrillation.

701
00:25:55.345 --> 00:25:58.348
- Holding compressions.
- Normal sinus.

702
00:25:58.431 --> 00:26:00.517
- Carotid. Strong carotid.
Okay. let's try for BP.

703
00:26:00.600 --> 00:26:02.185
- Why don't we check
after the shock?

704
00:26:02.227 --> 00:26:04.104
- 2024 ACLS guidelines.

705
00:26:04.187 --> 00:26:06.106
Patients can remain pulseless
for a little bit.

706
00:26:06.189 --> 00:26:07.566
even after successful defib.

707
00:26:07.649 --> 00:26:10.068
- He came back with one shock.
That's as good as it gets.

708
00:26:10.151 --> 00:26:12.529
- 104 over 68.
- Good squeeze. Good EF.

709
00:26:12.571 --> 00:26:14.531
- Spontaneous respirations.
Okay. let's lift him up.

710
00:26:14.614 --> 00:26:16.908
- He's breathing on his own--
excellent sign.

711
00:26:16.992 --> 00:26:18.243
- Oh. God.

712
00:26:18.326 --> 00:26:21.705
Can I touch him?
- Of course.

713
00:26:21.788 --> 00:26:23.081
- Oh. Mark.

714
00:26:23.164 --> 00:26:26.167
Hey.
- [groans softly]

715
00:26:26.209 --> 00:26:27.919
- Oh. shit.

716
00:26:28.003 --> 00:26:29.254
We need a gurney!

717
00:26:29.337 --> 00:26:31.089
Nancy?

718
00:26:31.172 --> 00:26:33.091
Mrs. Yee?

719
00:26:33.174 --> 00:26:34.384
Mrs. Yee?

720
00:26:34.426 --> 00:26:35.885
Weak carotid.
Shallow breaths.

721
00:26:35.927 --> 00:26:37.721
- Did she vasovagal
from stress?

722
00:26:37.762 --> 00:26:38.888
- Can't assume that.

723
00:26:38.930 --> 00:26:40.724
Positive seat belt si--
oh. shit.

724
00:26:40.765 --> 00:26:42.392
Hang two units of O-neg
on the rapid infuser.

725
00:26:42.475 --> 00:26:44.019
Somebody call Garcia.
Shit.

726
00:26:44.060 --> 00:26:45.854
We really should have insisted
on examining her.

727
00:26:45.895 --> 00:26:47.188
- Okay. I got the head.

728
00:26:47.230 --> 00:26:49.482
- Platelets are these
tiny things in the blood

729
00:26:49.566 --> 00:26:51.067
that help it clot.

730
00:26:51.109 --> 00:26:54.487
And thrombocytopenia is fancy
for "low platelets."

731
00:26:54.571 --> 00:26:56.906
which explains why your skin
bruises so easily.

732
00:26:56.990 --> 00:26:58.199
- And what causes it?

733
00:26:58.241 --> 00:27:00.243
- It's actually
her immune system

734
00:27:00.327 --> 00:27:02.329
that's causing
the destruction of platelets.

735
00:27:02.412 --> 00:27:04.331
Sometimes
it's a triggered response

736
00:27:04.414 --> 00:27:07.667
to. uh. an environmental factor
or virus.

737
00:27:07.751 --> 00:27:10.587
<i>- And what's the treatment?</i>
<i>What are you giving her?</i>

738
00:27:10.670 --> 00:27:13.214
- We'll be treating her
with high-dose steroids

739
00:27:13.256 --> 00:27:16.092
to suppress the immune system
and IV immunoglobulin.

740
00:27:16.176 --> 00:27:18.928
which reduces the destruction
of the platelets in the spleen.

741
00:27:18.970 --> 00:27:20.221
- Can I go home?

742
00:27:20.263 --> 00:27:22.223
- You're gonna have to stay
in the hospital

743
00:27:22.265 --> 00:27:23.892
for about three days

744
00:27:23.933 --> 00:27:26.227
to make sure
that the treatment is working.

745
00:27:26.269 --> 00:27:27.937
- Okay. Okay.

746
00:27:27.979 --> 00:27:29.939
So when can she get
a room in the hospital?

747
00:27:29.981 --> 00:27:31.608
- That is
an excellent question.

748
00:27:31.650 --> 00:27:33.151
I'm going to see
if I can make that happen

749
00:27:33.234 --> 00:27:34.277
sooner rather than later.

750
00:27:34.361 --> 00:27:36.237
but it might take a while.
- Okay.

751
00:27:36.279 --> 00:27:38.239
<i>- GPS says I should be there</i>
<i>by 11:00.</i>

752
00:27:38.281 --> 00:27:41.034
- Do you have any other
questions for me. ma'am?

753
00:27:41.117 --> 00:27:43.787
<i>- No. I'm sure I will.</i>
<i>but I'll let you go for now.</i>

754
00:27:43.870 --> 00:27:45.121
<i>Thank you. Benny.</i>

755
00:27:45.205 --> 00:27:46.373
- All right.
I'll see you when you get here.

756
00:27:46.456 --> 00:27:48.041
<i>- See you soon. baby.</i>
<i>I love you.</i>

757
00:27:48.124 --> 00:27:50.960
- Bye. Mom.
Love you too.

758
00:27:52.295 --> 00:27:54.047
- There you are.

759
00:27:54.130 --> 00:27:55.382
- And there you are.

760
00:27:55.465 --> 00:27:58.301
- Don't try to charm me.
You promised to stay put.

761
00:27:58.385 --> 00:28:00.053
- I was going
to come right back.

762
00:28:00.136 --> 00:28:01.888
My backside is killing me.

763
00:28:01.971 --> 00:28:05.141
I need to keep moving.
or I get all achy and stiff.

764
00:28:05.183 --> 00:28:08.228
- Well. I got you
this foam donut to sit on

765
00:28:08.311 --> 00:28:11.106
while we wait for your X-rays.
- Hmm.

766
00:28:11.147 --> 00:28:13.608
Dr. Hazel Eyes. it says here

767
00:28:13.650 --> 00:28:18.488
that it's only supposed to take
an hour or two for an X-ray.

768
00:28:18.571 --> 00:28:21.449
- Well. the patient passport
holiday edition

769
00:28:21.491 --> 00:28:23.159
would better reflect reality.

770
00:28:23.201 --> 00:28:25.453
It could be double that.

771
00:28:25.495 --> 00:28:27.205
- There's no need for reality.

772
00:28:27.288 --> 00:28:29.499
We romantics...

773
00:28:29.582 --> 00:28:33.002
prefer <i>la reve.</i> the dream.

774
00:28:33.086 --> 00:28:34.671
- We do. do we?

775
00:28:34.713 --> 00:28:36.715
<i>- Oui.</i>

776
00:28:36.798 --> 00:28:40.009
♪ <i>La mer</i>
<i>qu'on voit danser</i> ♪

777
00:28:40.093 --> 00:28:42.846
♪ <i>Le long des golfes clairs</i> ♪

778
00:28:42.887 --> 00:28:45.014
♪ <i>A des reflets</i>
<i>d'argent. la mer</i> ♪

779
00:28:45.098 --> 00:28:46.474
- [laughs]
Right.

780
00:28:46.516 --> 00:28:50.019
- ♪ <i>Des reflets</i>
<i>changeants sous la pluie</i> ♪

781
00:28:50.061 --> 00:28:52.272
- Hey. save a dance for me.

782
00:28:52.355 --> 00:28:54.858
- Uh. yeah. okay. I will.

783
00:28:54.941 --> 00:28:56.276
- Dr. McKay?
- Yes.

784
00:28:56.359 --> 00:28:57.527
This is Gretchen Williams.

785
00:28:57.569 --> 00:28:59.362
- Actually. it's Lambdin.
- Ah.

786
00:28:59.446 --> 00:29:01.614
- You called about my
ex-husband. Michael Williams.

787
00:29:01.698 --> 00:29:03.700
- Yeah. Yes. yes.
Thank you for coming in.

788
00:29:03.783 --> 00:29:06.035
You were. um. listed
as his emergency contact.

789
00:29:06.077 --> 00:29:07.370
- Yeah. I don't know why.

790
00:29:07.454 --> 00:29:10.165
We have been divorced
for years.

791
00:29:10.206 --> 00:29:11.499
Is he all right?

792
00:29:11.541 --> 00:29:14.669
- He's--he's going
through a lot right now.

793
00:29:14.711 --> 00:29:16.421
Would you like to see him?

794
00:29:18.381 --> 00:29:19.549
- Uh. okay.

795
00:29:19.632 --> 00:29:23.344
Leo. can you zoom in and please
hold it a little steadier?

796
00:29:23.386 --> 00:29:24.971
<i>- Okay.</i>

797
00:29:27.182 --> 00:29:28.558
- Okay.

798
00:29:28.600 --> 00:29:30.185
Atorvastatin.

799
00:29:30.226 --> 00:29:31.770
Simvastatin.

800
00:29:31.853 --> 00:29:33.062
Ezetimibe.

801
00:29:33.146 --> 00:29:35.607
Those are all
high-cholesterol medications.

802
00:29:35.690 --> 00:29:37.358
Can you go to the right?

803
00:29:37.400 --> 00:29:39.611
Lisinopril.

804
00:29:39.694 --> 00:29:41.613
Losartan. Propranolol.

805
00:29:41.696 --> 00:29:43.615
- Wait. wait. that's it.

806
00:29:43.698 --> 00:29:45.158
Wendy's pile.

807
00:29:45.241 --> 00:29:46.367
Yellowish bottle.

808
00:29:46.409 --> 00:29:48.495
little. round blue pills.
just like I said.

809
00:29:48.578 --> 00:29:50.538
- Propranolol?
- Bingo. little lady.

810
00:29:50.580 --> 00:29:52.999
- Okay. yeah. well. this makes
a lot of sense now.

811
00:29:53.082 --> 00:29:57.003
Um. propranolol is a
high-blood-pressure medication.

812
00:29:57.086 --> 00:29:59.881
Those are 20 milligrams each.

813
00:29:59.923 --> 00:30:02.050
and the starting dose
is 40 mgs.

814
00:30:02.091 --> 00:30:03.843
How many pills did you take?

815
00:30:03.927 --> 00:30:06.721
- No. ma'am. I-I went
just before I came here.

816
00:30:06.763 --> 00:30:08.431
- Dad.

817
00:30:08.473 --> 00:30:11.184
- Um--pill--how many pills
did you take?

818
00:30:11.267 --> 00:30:15.939
- Oh. uh.
I think four. maybe five.

819
00:30:16.022 --> 00:30:17.774
- That is a lot.
Okay.

820
00:30:17.857 --> 00:30:20.068
- Full stomach. mind you.

821
00:30:20.109 --> 00:30:23.279
- Well. um. the good news is.
it has a short half-life.

822
00:30:23.321 --> 00:30:25.907
so. um. we're gonna need
to keep you

823
00:30:25.949 --> 00:30:27.575
for about four hours
to monitor.

824
00:30:27.617 --> 00:30:29.786
But then you'll be able
to rejoin

825
00:30:29.869 --> 00:30:31.788
for all the late-afternoon
festivities.

826
00:30:31.871 --> 00:30:34.290
- All right.
- Whoo!

827
00:30:34.332 --> 00:30:36.000
[monitor beeping rapidly]
- Unit 3 and 4 running in.

828
00:30:36.084 --> 00:30:37.919
BP 84 over 56.
Heart rate 112.

829
00:30:37.961 --> 00:30:39.671
- Free fluid's
much bigger than before.

830
00:30:39.754 --> 00:30:41.756
- She's not turning the corner.
OR is holding a room.

831
00:30:41.798 --> 00:30:43.299
- I'll let the husband know.

832
00:30:43.383 --> 00:30:44.634
- Why did you guys wait
so long to check her?

833
00:30:44.717 --> 00:30:46.469
- Good vitals in the field.
No distress.

834
00:30:46.511 --> 00:30:47.804
She refused to sign in.

835
00:30:47.846 --> 00:30:49.138
- You should have
convinced her.

836
00:30:49.222 --> 00:30:50.557
- 20/20 hindsight.
She was stable.

837
00:30:50.640 --> 00:30:51.641
- Until she wasn't.

838
00:30:51.683 --> 00:30:53.434
- Next time. I'll use
my X-ray vision goggles.

839
00:30:53.476 --> 00:30:55.436
- Let's get her upstairs.

840
00:30:55.478 --> 00:30:58.147
- Got to do an accu-check
on my DKA patient.

841
00:30:58.231 --> 00:30:59.983
Thanks for the backup.

842
00:31:00.066 --> 00:31:01.860
- Anytime.

843
00:31:05.363 --> 00:31:08.074
- Now. try and lift
your arm. Mark.

844
00:31:10.034 --> 00:31:11.953
- I'm trying.
Can't do it.

845
00:31:11.995 --> 00:31:16.457
- But you are getting stronger.
and your speech is improving.

846
00:31:16.499 --> 00:31:18.793
- How did I lose
so much potassium?

847
00:31:18.835 --> 00:31:22.046
- You didn't lose it.
It got shifted into cells.

848
00:31:22.130 --> 00:31:24.340
When it comes back.
you'll return to normal.

849
00:31:24.382 --> 00:31:25.550
- Where's Nancy?

850
00:31:25.633 --> 00:31:27.635
- She had an injury to her
spleen right about here

851
00:31:27.677 --> 00:31:29.512
with some internal bleeding.

852
00:31:29.554 --> 00:31:30.847
- Oh. God.

853
00:31:30.930 --> 00:31:32.223
- She passed out
from blood loss.

854
00:31:32.307 --> 00:31:34.517
We were able to transfuse her.
and she's now on her way

855
00:31:34.559 --> 00:31:36.686
to surgery
to repair that damage.

856
00:31:36.769 --> 00:31:38.897
- This is my fault.

857
00:31:38.980 --> 00:31:42.567
She was trying to--
[sighs]

858
00:31:42.650 --> 00:31:47.030
She booked a trip
for us. for me.

859
00:31:47.113 --> 00:31:49.991
I fought her the whole time.
I've been--

860
00:31:50.033 --> 00:31:53.036
[sighs]

861
00:31:53.077 --> 00:31:54.871
Please don't--

862
00:31:54.913 --> 00:31:57.790
oh. my God.
please don't let her die.

863
00:31:57.874 --> 00:31:59.208
Please.

864
00:31:59.250 --> 00:32:02.003
- I can assure you
that she is in excellent hands.

865
00:32:04.047 --> 00:32:05.715
- Is this how it works?

866
00:32:05.757 --> 00:32:08.176
- How what works?

867
00:32:08.217 --> 00:32:10.720
- You think things
are important...

868
00:32:10.762 --> 00:32:14.223
that everything's so important.

869
00:32:14.265 --> 00:32:16.434
And then you end up here
and see.

870
00:32:19.479 --> 00:32:22.732
- Yeah. that is how it works.

871
00:32:22.815 --> 00:32:25.693
- No. it's a small hole.

872
00:32:25.735 --> 00:32:28.196
Like the size of a dime.
right. Doc?

873
00:32:28.237 --> 00:32:30.615
- Mm-hmm.
Yeah. even smaller.

874
00:32:30.698 --> 00:32:32.700
It's a minor enough procedure

875
00:32:32.742 --> 00:32:35.244
that most patients go home
the next day.

876
00:32:35.328 --> 00:32:36.371
- And then?

877
00:32:36.412 --> 00:32:38.539
- And then they'll know
what it is

878
00:32:38.581 --> 00:32:39.749
and how to treat it.

879
00:32:39.832 --> 00:32:42.961
Isn't that right?
- Yeah. exactly.

880
00:32:44.921 --> 00:32:47.799
- I'm sorry
that they called you.

881
00:32:47.882 --> 00:32:49.801
I never updated the form.
I guess.

882
00:32:49.884 --> 00:32:52.011
- No. no. it's okay.
I'm--

883
00:32:53.596 --> 00:32:57.350
You know. they called. and I
was just kind of surprised.

884
00:32:57.433 --> 00:32:59.435
[both chuckle]

885
00:32:59.477 --> 00:33:01.229
- Well. you didn't have
to come.

886
00:33:02.939 --> 00:33:04.148
- But I did.

887
00:33:07.652 --> 00:33:09.904
- I heard you got married.

888
00:33:09.946 --> 00:33:11.572
Congratulations.

889
00:33:11.614 --> 00:33:13.366
- Thank you.

890
00:33:15.284 --> 00:33:17.996
- I hope he treats you well.

891
00:33:19.789 --> 00:33:21.874
You deserve to be happy.

892
00:33:25.044 --> 00:33:27.130
- [sighs]

893
00:33:27.171 --> 00:33:31.300
I'm really sorry you're going
through this. Michael.

894
00:33:31.384 --> 00:33:33.511
- Yeah.

895
00:33:33.594 --> 00:33:36.472
Me too.

896
00:33:36.514 --> 00:33:39.559
But you know me--
I'm a survivor.

897
00:33:43.896 --> 00:33:48.359
- Why don't I-I leave you guys
to talk for a few minutes?

898
00:33:48.443 --> 00:33:51.029
I have a patient to check on.

899
00:33:52.405 --> 00:33:54.407
- Sure.
- Yeah.

900
00:33:55.908 --> 00:33:58.327
- Mr. Diaz should be improving
after 2 liters.

901
00:33:58.369 --> 00:33:59.746
Blood sugar?

902
00:33:59.829 --> 00:34:01.748
- Down from 521 to 436.

903
00:34:01.831 --> 00:34:03.082
- That's good. right?

904
00:34:03.166 --> 00:34:04.500
- Moving
in the right direction.

905
00:34:04.542 --> 00:34:06.669
Were you able to get ahold
of your mom?

906
00:34:06.711 --> 00:34:08.921
- Yes. She's on her way.
She doesn't have a car.

907
00:34:09.005 --> 00:34:11.340
She takes buses.
so it takes longer.

908
00:34:11.424 --> 00:34:14.177
I'm sorry.
- Don't be.

909
00:34:14.260 --> 00:34:17.805
Current insulin is 0.1 units
per kilo per hour.

910
00:34:17.847 --> 00:34:18.848
Next steps?

911
00:34:18.890 --> 00:34:20.516
- Once the glucose
is down to 250.

912
00:34:20.558 --> 00:34:23.186
reduce the insulin to
0.05 units per kilo per hour.

913
00:34:23.227 --> 00:34:24.812
- Because you can normalize
the blood sugar

914
00:34:24.854 --> 00:34:27.231
before you clear the ketones.
and you don't get hypoglycemia.

915
00:34:27.315 --> 00:34:30.026
- But as treatment continues.
you'll have to give IV dextrose

916
00:34:30.068 --> 00:34:32.487
to keep the blood glucose
in between 150 and 200

917
00:34:32.528 --> 00:34:33.738
while the insulin drip
clears the ketones.

918
00:34:33.821 --> 00:34:35.531
- Obviously.

919
00:34:35.615 --> 00:34:37.366
- I'm sorry. what?

920
00:34:39.077 --> 00:34:40.328
- Got it.

921
00:34:40.369 --> 00:34:42.205
- Duante. what are you doing
in there. son?

922
00:34:42.288 --> 00:34:43.706
- I'm a rabbit.

923
00:34:43.748 --> 00:34:46.000
grabbing all the carrots
before the farmer gets me.

924
00:34:46.042 --> 00:34:47.585
- Keep going.

925
00:34:47.668 --> 00:34:51.214
This is a Katz extractor
with a tiny balloon at the end.

926
00:34:51.297 --> 00:34:53.341
What we're gonna do is. we're
gonna slip it past the bead.

927
00:34:53.382 --> 00:34:54.926
inflate the balloon.
try to pull out the bead.

928
00:34:55.009 --> 00:34:57.178
- Is it painful?
- No. he's--he's numbed up.

929
00:34:57.220 --> 00:34:58.721
- Made it to level three.

930
00:34:58.763 --> 00:35:00.056
- And pretty distracted.

931
00:35:00.139 --> 00:35:02.350
- Dad's gonna hold
your head still. okay?

932
00:35:02.391 --> 00:35:04.894
- Look up.
- Okay.

933
00:35:04.977 --> 00:35:08.815
Now go back. perpendicular.

934
00:35:08.898 --> 00:35:10.983
below the turbinates.

935
00:35:12.318 --> 00:35:14.821
You guys ever hear
of John O'Donohue?

936
00:35:14.904 --> 00:35:16.072
- Mm-mm.
- No.

937
00:35:16.114 --> 00:35:17.490
- I've been reading him
a lot lately.

938
00:35:17.573 --> 00:35:20.910
He's got this book
of. um. blessings.

939
00:35:20.952 --> 00:35:23.204
And there's this one
about fatherhood.

940
00:35:23.246 --> 00:35:25.915
{\an8}Really stuck with me.
[bead clatters]

941
00:35:25.957 --> 00:35:28.292
{\an8}Voilà.
One red bead.

942
00:35:28.376 --> 00:35:30.753
- Yeah?
How's it go?

943
00:35:30.795 --> 00:35:34.590
- The ending goes.
"May you be gentle and loving.

944
00:35:34.674 --> 00:35:36.551
"clear and sure.

945
00:35:36.592 --> 00:35:39.428
"May you trust
in the unseen Providence

946
00:35:39.470 --> 00:35:41.764
"that has chosen you
to be a family.

947
00:35:41.806 --> 00:35:45.810
"May you stand sure
on your ground and know

948
00:35:45.893 --> 00:35:49.105
"that every grace you need
will unfold before you

949
00:35:49.188 --> 00:35:51.607
like all the mornings
of your life."

950
00:35:51.691 --> 00:35:53.734
- Hmm. That's good.

951
00:35:53.776 --> 00:35:58.698
- I'd add. support your woman
and pack good snacks.

952
00:35:58.781 --> 00:36:00.283
- That's beautiful.

953
00:36:00.324 --> 00:36:03.244
And it turns out. there's
no handbook for fatherhood.

954
00:36:03.286 --> 00:36:07.248
So I will take
all the wisdom I can.

955
00:36:07.290 --> 00:36:10.251
{\an8}[bead clatters]
Blue bead out.

956
00:36:15.131 --> 00:36:16.632
- Anything else?

957
00:36:16.674 --> 00:36:19.260
- You tell me.
I have my own report to do.

958
00:36:19.302 --> 00:36:20.303
Anything I left out?

959
00:36:20.386 --> 00:36:21.721
- Labs are back on that kid.

960
00:36:21.804 --> 00:36:23.264
- We'll follow up
with Mr. Davis.

961
00:36:23.306 --> 00:36:26.184
- Yeah. when Mr. Davis
comes off the ceiling.

962
00:36:29.187 --> 00:36:31.272
- Jackson Davis...

963
00:36:31.314 --> 00:36:33.608
tox screen negative
for cocaine.

964
00:36:33.649 --> 00:36:38.029
amphetamines. marijuana.
PCP. benzos. and opioids.

965
00:36:38.112 --> 00:36:40.323
- So no drugs in his system?
- Nope.

966
00:36:40.406 --> 00:36:42.658
- Taser barbs on the back
of the victim's neck?

967
00:36:42.700 --> 00:36:44.160
- Yep.

968
00:36:46.996 --> 00:36:49.040
- Changes things. Tony.

969
00:36:49.123 --> 00:36:50.666
- Hey. Louie.
- [groans]

970
00:36:50.750 --> 00:36:53.502
- How we doing?
- Not so good.

971
00:36:53.544 --> 00:36:55.838
I could really use a drink.

972
00:36:55.880 --> 00:36:58.507
I f-feel a-a little empty.

973
00:36:58.549 --> 00:37:00.051
- Okay. well. empty
is what we want.

974
00:37:00.134 --> 00:37:02.178
And it looks like we are there.

975
00:37:02.220 --> 00:37:05.598
- Hey. well. if I can't get
a drink. my tooth.

976
00:37:05.681 --> 00:37:07.099
You--you got to do something.

977
00:37:07.183 --> 00:37:08.309
- We're gonna get
right to that.

978
00:37:08.351 --> 00:37:12.021
Let's hang some IV antibiotics.
3 grams of Unasyn.

979
00:37:12.104 --> 00:37:14.106
- Excellent.

980
00:37:14.190 --> 00:37:15.358
- He's gonna be right back.

981
00:37:15.399 --> 00:37:16.776
We're gonna numb it up
and drain it.

982
00:37:16.859 --> 00:37:18.611
Ten minutes. tops. okay?
- Oh.

983
00:37:18.694 --> 00:37:21.197
- Hey. uh. you said
you met Mr. Zambelli.

984
00:37:21.239 --> 00:37:23.282
the fireworks guy.
on the field.

985
00:37:23.366 --> 00:37:24.325
What field was that?

986
00:37:24.367 --> 00:37:27.995
- Uh. n-no more talking.
You got to fix my tooth.

987
00:37:28.037 --> 00:37:29.664
- Yeah. deal.

988
00:37:29.705 --> 00:37:31.374
- [grunts]

989
00:37:35.795 --> 00:37:38.381
- You're Muslim?

990
00:37:38.464 --> 00:37:41.008
- I am.

991
00:37:41.050 --> 00:37:42.510
- Thank you.

992
00:37:42.551 --> 00:37:44.470
- Oh. for what?

993
00:37:45.763 --> 00:37:48.099
- After the shooting.
it was the Muslims

994
00:37:48.182 --> 00:37:51.602
that came together for us
in support and...

995
00:37:51.686 --> 00:37:53.396
walked with us.

996
00:37:53.479 --> 00:37:55.064
You raised money.

997
00:37:55.106 --> 00:37:56.774
You...

998
00:37:56.857 --> 00:37:59.694
paid for all the funerals.

999
00:37:59.735 --> 00:38:02.238
Anyway...

1000
00:38:02.321 --> 00:38:03.739
thank you.
[door opens]

1001
00:38:03.781 --> 00:38:06.867
- Hello.
How's it going in here?

1002
00:38:06.909 --> 00:38:08.744
Did I miss all the gross stuff?

1003
00:38:08.786 --> 00:38:10.746
- Timed it perfectly.
- Excellent.

1004
00:38:10.830 --> 00:38:13.082
My job is all about delegation
and time management.

1005
00:38:13.165 --> 00:38:15.418
- Oh. not for much longer.
- That is very true.

1006
00:38:15.459 --> 00:38:17.003
- W-why for not longer?

1007
00:38:17.086 --> 00:38:20.006
- Because tomorrow I am leaving
to go on sabbatical.

1008
00:38:20.089 --> 00:38:23.259
- He's leaving us for
three months on a motorcycle.

1009
00:38:23.301 --> 00:38:25.845
- Motorcycle?
You're joking.

1010
00:38:25.928 --> 00:38:28.597
Why would you do this?
- Why? Why?

1011
00:38:28.639 --> 00:38:30.766
Why? Because--
- You're middle-aged man.

1012
00:38:30.850 --> 00:38:32.518
Don't be stupid.

1013
00:38:32.601 --> 00:38:34.478
- Don't hold back.
Tell me how you really feel.

1014
00:38:34.562 --> 00:38:37.106
- Forgive me for being blunt.
Dr. Robinavitch.

1015
00:38:37.148 --> 00:38:39.734
but how old are you. huh--50?

1016
00:38:39.775 --> 00:38:41.777
- Ish.
- Ish.

1017
00:38:41.819 --> 00:38:45.781
50-ish-year-old man
on a motorcycle--

1018
00:38:45.823 --> 00:38:46.782
very sad.

1019
00:38:46.824 --> 00:38:48.451
[laughter]

1020
00:38:48.534 --> 00:38:51.579
[indistinct chatter]

1021
00:38:57.960 --> 00:38:59.712
- I. um...

1022
00:39:01.505 --> 00:39:03.758
I-I-I don't know what to say.

1023
00:39:03.799 --> 00:39:06.052
Have you ever heard of ITP?

1024
00:39:06.135 --> 00:39:07.136
I never did.

1025
00:39:09.305 --> 00:39:11.474
I really appreciate you
bringing her here. okay?

1026
00:39:11.515 --> 00:39:13.768
- Of course.
What do you think I am?

1027
00:39:13.809 --> 00:39:15.102
Oh. that's right.

1028
00:39:15.144 --> 00:39:16.729
You think I'm some kind
of child abuser.

1029
00:39:16.812 --> 00:39:18.397
- No. I never said that--
- The fuck you didn't.

1030
00:39:18.481 --> 00:39:20.483
In front of all those people.
you made it sound like

1031
00:39:20.524 --> 00:39:21.650
she might have
been getting hurt

1032
00:39:21.692 --> 00:39:23.903
while I was watching her.
like it was my fault.

1033
00:39:23.986 --> 00:39:25.154
- You basically said
the same thing about me.

1034
00:39:25.237 --> 00:39:26.822
- No. I said that
you guys roughhouse--

1035
00:39:26.906 --> 00:39:28.491
that's all--because you do.

1036
00:39:28.532 --> 00:39:30.659
- You know I would never hurt
my daughter.

1037
00:39:30.743 --> 00:39:32.787
- Actually. I don't.

1038
00:39:32.828 --> 00:39:35.664
I've known you six months.
You could be anybody.

1039
00:39:35.748 --> 00:39:37.792
- Okay. well. I am sorry
for what I said. okay?

1040
00:39:37.833 --> 00:39:39.502
I was upset.
and I-I was worried.

1041
00:39:39.543 --> 00:39:41.003
And I just--
I said something stupid.

1042
00:39:41.087 --> 00:39:42.338
And I just--
- You think?

1043
00:39:42.421 --> 00:39:43.631
- Will you just fucking
let me finish?

1044
00:39:43.672 --> 00:39:45.716
- You are finished!

1045
00:39:45.800 --> 00:39:46.926
We're finished.

1046
00:39:49.095 --> 00:39:50.721
- Well. happy fucking
Fourth of July.

1047
00:39:50.805 --> 00:39:52.098
- Yeah. happy Independence Day.

1048
00:39:54.266 --> 00:39:57.144
[indistinct chatter]

1049
00:39:57.186 --> 00:39:59.855
- Excuse me?
[grunts]

1050
00:39:59.939 --> 00:40:01.857
- Yes?
What can I do for you?

1051
00:40:01.899 --> 00:40:04.026
- Uh. my wife and I
were in an accident.

1052
00:40:04.110 --> 00:40:07.405
Um. she's in surgery right now.

1053
00:40:07.488 --> 00:40:09.365
Would you mind holding
my phone up for me

1054
00:40:09.448 --> 00:40:11.867
so I could record
a message for her?

1055
00:40:11.909 --> 00:40:13.536
- Of course I will.

1056
00:40:13.577 --> 00:40:14.537
Happy to.

1057
00:40:14.578 --> 00:40:17.289
Oh. good. I have the same one.

1058
00:40:17.373 --> 00:40:19.125
I know how this works.

1059
00:40:21.085 --> 00:40:23.337
Okay.

1060
00:40:23.379 --> 00:40:24.505
Ready?

1061
00:40:24.547 --> 00:40:26.841
Go.
- [clears throat]

1062
00:40:26.882 --> 00:40:28.008
[sighs]

1063
00:40:28.050 --> 00:40:30.177
Hi. my love.

1064
00:40:30.219 --> 00:40:33.013
[clears throat]
So. uh...

1065
00:40:33.055 --> 00:40:36.976
I was listening
to this couple argue. uh...

1066
00:40:37.059 --> 00:40:38.853
and they were yelling.

1067
00:40:38.894 --> 00:40:41.439
Both so angry.

1068
00:40:43.357 --> 00:40:47.945
And I just wanted you
to know. um...

1069
00:40:48.028 --> 00:40:49.947
that I was wrong.

1070
00:40:50.030 --> 00:40:54.869
I was so wrong. and--
and I'm sorry about all of it.

1071
00:40:54.910 --> 00:40:56.370
Uh...

1072
00:40:58.080 --> 00:40:59.582
- Hey.

1073
00:40:59.623 --> 00:41:01.542
How you doing?
- [sighs]

1074
00:41:01.584 --> 00:41:03.586
I haven't seen him
in. like. four years.

1075
00:41:03.627 --> 00:41:06.422
- Oh.
I can't imagine.

1076
00:41:06.464 --> 00:41:08.591
That must have been--
- So crazy.

1077
00:41:08.632 --> 00:41:10.843
You know. things were not good
at the end.

1078
00:41:10.926 --> 00:41:13.429
He was
a really different person.

1079
00:41:13.471 --> 00:41:17.850
Huge temper. not like
when we first got married.

1080
00:41:17.933 --> 00:41:19.852
- I'm so sorry.

1081
00:41:21.145 --> 00:41:23.105
- Could that mass
have been there for a while

1082
00:41:23.189 --> 00:41:26.275
and only recently got worse?

1083
00:41:26.317 --> 00:41:27.568
- Yes.

1084
00:41:27.610 --> 00:41:30.362
- Could it be responsible
for how much he changed?

1085
00:41:30.446 --> 00:41:32.615
You know. his--
his moods and tempers?

1086
00:41:32.656 --> 00:41:36.785
He was--he was getting
into fights with strangers.

1087
00:41:36.869 --> 00:41:39.371
- It's possible.
[sighs]

1088
00:41:45.961 --> 00:41:47.421
- Oh.

1089
00:41:49.757 --> 00:41:51.550
Thank you.

1090
00:41:53.719 --> 00:41:57.765
Um. unless he's asked you
to change it.

1091
00:41:57.806 --> 00:42:01.101
would you please leave me as...

1092
00:42:01.143 --> 00:42:02.686
the emergency contact?

1093
00:42:02.770 --> 00:42:04.772
- Yeah. absolutely.

1094
00:42:09.944 --> 00:42:13.155
[door opens]

1095
00:42:13.239 --> 00:42:15.908
[sighs]

1096
00:42:15.991 --> 00:42:18.452
- Okay. I'm sending
Mrs. Kovalenko home

1097
00:42:18.494 --> 00:42:19.662
with burn dressing

1098
00:42:19.703 --> 00:42:21.747
but not before
she turned my sabbatical

1099
00:42:21.830 --> 00:42:24.458
into a midlife crisis.
- No comment.

1100
00:42:24.500 --> 00:42:26.460
- Wound check. two days.
- Got it.

1101
00:42:26.502 --> 00:42:28.003
- What about Kylie.
this little girl?

1102
00:42:28.087 --> 00:42:29.964
She gone up yet?
- Hopefully soon.

1103
00:42:30.005 --> 00:42:32.174
- Hey. we're starting to clear
some space around here.

1104
00:42:32.216 --> 00:42:34.260
- Yep.
[telephone ringing]

1105
00:42:34.343 --> 00:42:37.888
PTMC Charge Nurse.
Go ahead. Medic Command.

1106
00:42:39.431 --> 00:42:41.100
Is this a drill?

1107
00:42:41.183 --> 00:42:42.268
Is this a joke?

1108
00:42:42.351 --> 00:42:43.686
It's the Fourth
of fucking July.

1109
00:42:48.691 --> 00:42:50.401
Got it. Thanks.

1110
00:42:50.484 --> 00:42:52.236
- What's up?
- Westbridge has a Code Black

1111
00:42:52.319 --> 00:42:54.196
and is closing
to internal disaster.

1112
00:42:54.238 --> 00:42:56.198
Central's diverting all
their ambulance traffic to us.

1113
00:42:56.282 --> 00:42:58.367
- What's the issue?
- Comspec didn't say.

1114
00:42:58.409 --> 00:42:59.410
- Shit. it could be anything

1115
00:42:59.493 --> 00:43:01.036
from a flooding toilet
to a power outage.

1116
00:43:01.078 --> 00:43:02.663
How long?
- Didn't know.

1117
00:43:02.705 --> 00:43:04.999
- A couple of doctors
probably got the holiday flu.

1118
00:43:05.040 --> 00:43:06.917
and they're understaffed.

1119
00:43:07.001 --> 00:43:08.544
- [chuckles]

1120
00:43:08.586 --> 00:43:11.839
How come? How long?
How many?

1121
00:43:11.880 --> 00:43:13.882
Mm. mm. mm.

1122
00:43:13.966 --> 00:43:17.219
Sounds like
a betting grid to me.

1123
00:43:17.303 --> 00:43:19.305
We are back.

1124
00:43:20.723 --> 00:43:23.976
- Oh. I should have left
last night.
